    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-17T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-17T03:00:00-05:00" n="803"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d803">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 European War/10–1744: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The American Representative on the Advisory Council for
                        Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-17T09:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 17, 1944—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>537. Italian Foreign Office has informed SAC<note n="46" xml:id="d803fn1">Supreme
                        Allied Commander (Mediterranean).</note> of a communication received from
                    National Committee of Liberation in Northern Italy reporting a sharp increase in
                    German atrocities in Northern Italy and has requested urgent intervention of
                    United Nations in this matter to cause Germans to cease atrocities.</p>
                <p>At request of SAC, the ACI<note n="46a" xml:id="d803fn2">Advisory Council for
                        Italy.</note> will consider at its next meeting scheduled for October 20 the
                    problem of German atrocities in Northern Italy with a view to advising on means
                    of inducing Germans to cease.</p>
                <p>537 to Dept., repeated London as 34, Moscow as 29 and by hand to AmPolAd<note
                        n="47" xml:id="d803fn3">The American Political Adviser on the Staff of the
                        Allied Commander, Mediterranean Theater, Theodore J. Hohenthal.</note> as
                    77.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
